msIdentifier.collection: John Frederick Lewis Collection of European Manuscripts

msContents.summary: This manuscript is an early fourteenth-century New Testament, possibly written in Italy. The end of the manuscript, including the end of Acts and the Apocalypse, is lacking, and a nonbiblical work, the Summa contra hereticos, appears between the Gospels and the Epistles. It is decorated with rubrics, running titles, and scrollwork initials in red.

msItem.title: Text, beginning with Heretici qui habent errorem suum

supportDesc.extent: iii+142+iii; 147 x 103 mm bound to 155 x 108 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, upper right recto

layoutDesc.layout: Two columns of thirty-nine lines; hard point ruling, prickings visible; written area: 147 x 103 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: Red-ink scroll-work initials throughout; place left for an illuminated initial at the beginning of Matthew
Inside front coverBookplate, John Frederick Lewis

binding.p: Eighteenth-century French brown calf with gilt dentelles and red-marbled endpapers; mottled edges on leaves

history.provenance: Unidentified Jesuit College, 1767; Sold by Thomas Thorpe (Cat. 1836, no. 1268) to Sir Thomas Phillipps; T. FitzRoy Fenwick, 1891; John Frederick Lewis, Philadelphia; given by his widow, Anne Baker Lewis, to the Free Library of Philadelphia in 1936
